# Playwright Page Object Model (POM)
1️⃣ What is Page Object Model (POM)?
Page Object Model is a design pattern used in test automation to organize test code.
In POM, 
    1. Each web page in the application is represented as a class
    2. This class contains:
        -> Locators
        -> Methods to perform actions on the page.
So instead of writing everythin in the test file , we separate page actions from test logic.

2️⃣ Why Page Object Model is Used
Wihtout POM ,
    1. Locators
    2. Actions
    3. Test logic
are all written inside the test file , making it messy.
Problems:
    1. Hard to maintain
    2. Code duplication
    3. Difficult to reuse
POM solves this by organizing code properly

3️⃣ Basic Idea of POM
Example application page:
    Login page
    ----------
        username field
        password field
        login button
    
    In POM , we can create class like this:
        LoginPage
        ├── locators
        ├── actions
        └── methods
Then tests will call these methods instead of interacting with elements directly.

4️⃣ Folder Structure (Playwright + Python)
Typical structure:
    project/
    │
    ├── tests/
    │     test_login.py
    │
    ├── pages/
    │     login_page.py
    │     dashboard_page.py
    │
    ├── conftest.py
    │
    └── playwright.config

Explanation:
    Folder & Purpose
    ----------------
    1. tests -> contains test cases
    2. pages -> contains page classes
    3. conftest.py -> fixtures
    4. config -> Playwright settings

5️⃣ Page Object Model Flow
Flow of execution
-----------------
Test File
   ↓
Page Object Class
   ↓
Playwright Page
   ↓
Browser

Example:
--------
    test_login.py
    ↓
    LoginPage.login()
    ↓
    page.fill()
    page.click()
    ↓
    Browser performs actions

6️⃣ Example Without POM (Bad Practice)
def test_login(page):
    page.goto("https://example.com/login")

    page.fill("#username","admin")
    page.fill("#password","admin123")
    page.click("#login")

    assert page.url == "https://example.com/dashboard"


Problems:
    1. Locators inside test
    2. Hard to reuse
    3. If locator changes -> all tests fail

7️⃣ Example With POM (Good Practice)
LoginPage class
---------------
class LoginPage:

    def __init__(self, page):
        self.page = page
        self.username = page.locator("#username")
        self.password = page.locator("#password")
        self.login_btn = page.locator("#login")

    def goto_login_page(self):
        self.page.goto("https://example.com/login")

    def login(self, user, pwd):
        self.username.fill(user)
        self.password.fill(pwd)
        self.login_btn.click()


test_login.py
-------------
from pages.login_page import LoginPage

def test_login(page):

    login = LoginPage(page)

    login.goto_login_page()
    login.login("admin","admin123")


Now:
    1. Test is clean
    2. Logic is resuable

8️⃣ Important Components in POM
    1️⃣ Page Class
    Represents the web page
    Example:
        class LoginPage:

    2️⃣ Constructor
    Used to initialize playwright page object
    def __init__(self, page):
        self.page = page
    
    3️⃣ Locators
    Store element selectors
    Example:
        self.username = page.locator("#username")
        self.password = page.locator("#password")
    
    4️⃣ Methods / Actions
    Methods perform user actions
    Example:
        def login(self, user, pwd):

    Inside methods:
        fill() , click() , press() , select_option()
    
9️⃣ Advantages of POM
1. Code reusability
    Same page methods used in many tests
2. Easy maintenance
    If locator changes:
        Change in one place only
3. Cleaner test case
    Test files only contain test logic
4. Better readability
    Test becomes human readable
    Examples:
        login_page.login("admin","admin123")
5. Scalable Framework
    Suitable for large framework frameworks.

🔟 POM With Assertions Example
PageClass
---------
class DashboardPage:

    def __init__(self,page):
        self.page = page
        self.heading = page.locator("h1")

    def get_heading(self):
        return self.heading.text_content()

Test
----
def test_dashboard(page):
    dashboard = DashboardPage(page)
    assert dashboard.get_heading() == "Dashboard"

1️⃣1️⃣ Best Practices for POM
1. Keep locators inside page class
    Bad:
        page.locator("#login")
    Good:
        self.login_btn
2. Use meaningful method names
Example:
    login()
    search_product()
    add_to_cart()
    logout()
3. Avoid assertions inside page classes
    Assertions should stay in test files.
    Bad:
        assert self.heading.is_visible()
    Good:
        expect(dashboard.heading).to_be_visible()
4. One class = One page
    Example:
        LoginPage
        HomePage
        DashboardPage
        CartPage

